''Oddfellows'' has received mostly positive reviews since its release. Review aggregation website [[Metacritic]] lists the album as having an average rating of 79 out of 100, based on eighteen reviews.<ref name="metacritic">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/oddfellows/tomahawk/critic-reviews |title=Critic reviews for Oddfellows |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> 

Writing for [[AllRovi]], Jason Lymangrover rated the album four stars out of five. Lymangrover praised both Dunn's bass playing and Patton's vocals, and felt that the album was "a welcome return to form", similar in sound to their 2001 debut album.<ref name="allrovi">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/oddfellows-mw0002435283 |title=Oddfellows <U+2013> Tomahawk: Songs, Reviews, Credits and Awards |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[AllRovi]] |first=Jason |last=Lymangrover |accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> Jason Heller of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' awarded the album an "A<U+2212>". Heller felt that ''Oddfellows'' featured "tighter songs and sturdier structures" than the band's previous work, which he considered comparable to that of a [[jam band]].<ref name="av rev">{{cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/tomahawk-oddfellows,91668/ |title=Tomahawk: Oddfellows {{!}} Music {{!}} MusicalWork Review |first=Jason |last=Heller |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[The Onion]] |date=January 29, 2013 |accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> [[Drowned in Sound]]'s Kev Eddy scored ''Oddfellows'' eight out of ten, comparing it favorably to the work of Patton's earlier band [[Faith No More]]. Eddy felt that the album was less experimental than previous Tomahawk records, but that its restraint was positive and accessible.<ref name="drown">{{cite web |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/17435/reviews/4145975 |title=Tomahawk <U+2013> Oddfellows / Releases |publisher=[[Drowned in Sound]] |first=Kev |last=Eddy |date=January 25, 2013 |accessdate= January 30, 2013}}</ref> Paige Camisasca of ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' magazine scored the album four out of five, calling it a "surprising, thoroughly consistent return-to-form".<ref name="revolver">{{cite web |url=http://www.revolvermag.com/reviews/review-tomahawk-oddfellows.html |title=Review: Tomahawk <U+2013> Oddfellows |work=[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]] |first=Paige |last=Camisasca |date=January 15, 2013 |accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> Camiscasca considered "Stone Letter", "Waratorium" and "I.O.U." to be the album's highlights, and earmarked it as "the first contender for hard-rock album of the year".<ref name="revolver"/>

''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine's Grayson Currin rated ''Oddfellows'' seven out of ten, finding that it "presents a tide of ideas, information, and intrigue".<ref name="spin">{{cite web |url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/tomahawk-oddfellows-ipecac |title=Album Review: Tomahawk <U+2013> Oddfellows |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |first=Grayson |last=Currin  |date=January 28, 2013 |accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> Currin felt that the album attempted to blend both art rock and mainstream rock sounds, but was more successful when aiming solely for experimentation<U+2014>finding "I Can Almost See Them" and "A Thousand Eyes" to be examples of this.<ref name="spin"/> [[Consequence of Sound]] writer Len Comaratta awarded ''Oddfellows'' three stars out of five, finding that Dunn's bass playing improves the band's sound without altering it radically.<ref name="cos">{{cite web |url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/01/album-review-tomahawk-oddfellows/ |title=Album Review: Tomahawk <U+2013> Oddfellows |first=Len |last=Comaratta |publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=January 28, 2013 |accessdate=January 30, 2013}}</ref> Comaratta felt that the album rewarded patient listeners but did not provide memorable hooks or melodies, and compared its "laid back" sound to that of [[Nick Cave and the Bad Seeds]].<ref name="cos"/>

Cole Waterman of [[PopMatters]] awarded the album a score of eight out of ten, finding the record to be the group's "most accessible by far".<ref name="matters">{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/167557-tomahawk-oddfellows/ |title=Tomahawk: Oddfellows |publisher=[[PopMatters]] |first=Cole |last=Waterman |date=February 4, 2013 |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> Waterman described the album's composition as "catchy", finding it to be an appropriate response to the band's previous album ''Anonymous''; he also highlighted the "absurdist" tone of the record's lyrics<U+2014>pointing out "South Paw" and "Waratorium" as particular examples of this.<ref name="matters"/> [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Paul Thompson scored ''Oddfellows'' 6.8 out of ten, considering it "Tomahawk's most straightforward, stripped-down release to date".<ref name="pf rev">{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17602-oddfellows/ |title=Tomahawk: Oddfellows {{!}} Album Reviews |publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]] |date=February 4, 2013 |first=Paul |last=Thompson |accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> Thompson considered the group's main dynamic to consist of Denison's compositions and Patton's vocals, finding that bass player Dunn "hangs back here, ably holding down the low end without overasserting himself".<ref name="pf rev"/> Thompson also debated the effect that the album's short germination period had on its overall composition, believing that the brief recording time lent the record "a feeling that, whenever you get these guys in the same room, this music [...] just comes tearing out".<ref name="pf rev"/>

